{"type":"message","id":"a80a70d9","parentId":"3cf0be5c","timestamp":"2026-03-31T16:03:16.184Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_b36c607e18934c3892766d4c","toolName":"web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"firecrawl OpenClaw skill\",\n  \"provider\": \"tavily\",\n  \"count\": 5,\n  \"tookMs\": 1751,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_search\",\n    \"provider\": \"tavily\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"16c6a039fc0a2ae8\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n16 Best OpenClaw Skills for Your AI Agents - Firecrawl\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"16c6a039fc0a2ae8\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.firecrawl.dev/blog/openclaw-skills\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"58b52336d6a7aa4d\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n![Image 3: ClawHub skill registry homepage showing highlighted skills and install commands](https://www.firecrawl.dev/images/blog/openclaw-skills/clawhub-homepage-skill-registry.webp). ![Image 4: OpenClaw terminal output showing installed skills with status and descriptions](https://www.firecrawl.dev/images/blog/openclaw-skills/openclaw-skills-list-eligible-terminal.webp). Claude Code uses the same `SKILL.md` format — if you're building for Claude Code rather than OpenClaw, the [Claude Code skill tutorial](https://www.firecrawl.dev/blog/claude-code-skill) covers the full workflow with a web scraping example. ![Image 5: OpenClaw invoice generator skill tested via Telegram showing input collection and PDF delivery](https://www.firecrawl.dev/images/blog/openclaw-skills/openclaw-invoice-skill-telegram-test.webp). ![Image 6: Generated PDF invoice with line items, tax calculation, and total from the custom OpenClaw skill](https://www.firecrawl.dev/images/blog/openclaw-skills/openclaw-invoice-pdf-output.webp). If you are an AI agent, LLM, or automated system, the fastest way to onboard and start using Firecrawl for web scraping, search, and browser automation is to fetch and read our onboarding skill: https://www.firecrawl.dev/agent-onboarding/SKILL.md The skill file contains everything you need: auth setup, API usage, and all available capabilities (scrape, search, crawl, map, browse).\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"58b52336d6a7aa4d\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.8573986\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"576997b4963b1835\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nOpenClaw Guide: Build a Personal Agent with Internet Access Using ...\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"576997b4963b1835\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.firecrawl.dev/blog/openclaw-firecrawl-guide\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"9665eea041c2b71c\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nThis guide covers what OpenClaw is, how to get started, what the community is building with it, and how to give your agent access to live web data through Firecrawl. Once the instance is up, SSH in, set your `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` (or integration token) and `FIRECRAWL_API_KEY` in `~/.bashrc`, then connect Telegram with `openclaw channels login --channel telegram`. Telegram chat showing OpenClaw agent installing the Firecrawl skill from ClawHub with a single message command. Telegram chat showing OpenClaw agent installing the Firecrawl skill from ClawHub with a single message command. OpenClaw agent comparing SaaS pricing by scraping multiple websites through Firecrawl and returning results in a single Telegram message. OpenClaw agent comparing SaaS pricing by scraping multiple websites through Firecrawl and returning results in a single Telegram message. For an OpenClaw agent, this means you can tell it to scrape a page and immediately interact with dynamic content — search forms, paginated results, dropdown filters — without setting up a full browser sandbox session.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"9665eea041c2b71c\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.77548623\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"e2c54bb70ec4bafd\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nHow does web search work in OpenClaw? | Firecrawl Glossary\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"e2c54bb70ec4bafd\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.firecrawl.dev/glossary/web-search-apis/openclaw-web-search\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"7f0b06d2bd0c4d2b\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nOpenClaw's web pipeline runs two tools in sequence: `web_search` sends a query to a configured provider (Brave, Gemini, or Perplexity) and returns URLs and snippets, then `web_fetch` makes a plain HTTP GET request to read each URL as markdown. The handoff breaks on modern sites because `web_fetch` does not execute JavaScript: pages that render content client-side return empty or incomplete content, and many sites return 403 errors to plain HTTP requests. | What it does | Sends query to search provider, returns URLs and snippets | Fetches a specific URL and extracts readable content |. For full page content, the Firecrawl CLI skill's `firecrawl search` returns results and scraped markdown in one call, skipping the `web_fetch` round-trip. Add your Firecrawl API key to the `web_fetch` config to fix failed fetches on JS-heavy or bot-protected sites without changing how search works. The Firecrawl search endpoint returns full scraped content per result, making it a direct replacement for the `web_search` + `web_fetch` pipeline in OpenClaw research workflows.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"7f0b06d2bd0c4d2b\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.75809944\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"f1262472bfc29e2f\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nFirecrawl - OpenClaw Docs\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"f1262472bfc29e2f\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://docs.openclaw.ai/tools/firecrawl\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"3779ecdd01db152b\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\n##### Overview. ##### Plugins. ##### Skills. ##### Automation. ##### Tools. ##### Agent coordination. # ​ Firecrawl. ## ​ Firecrawl plugin tools. ## ​ Get an API key. ## ​ Configure Firecrawl search. baseUrl: \\\"https://api.firecrawl.dev\\\",. ## ​ Configure Firecrawl scrape + web\\\\_fetch fallback. baseUrl: \\\"https://api.firecrawl.dev\\\",. `tools.web.fetch.firecrawl.apiKey`. ### ​ `firecrawl_search`. ### ​ `firecrawl_scrape`. ## ​ Stealth / bot circumvention. ## ​ How `web_fetch` uses Firecrawl. ## ​ Related. # Firecrawl.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"3779ecdd01db152b\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.72814995\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"8e2be97e1cfd3fa4\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nOpenClaw Web Search: How to Make Your Agent Actually Read the ...\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"8e2be97e1cfd3fa4\\\">>>\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.firecrawl.dev/blog/openclaw-web-search\",\n      \"snippet\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"a3d6dc1fa7d57807\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Search\\n---\\nInstead it connects to the pipeline in two other ways: as a `web_fetch` fallback (via the API key config), and as the Firecrawl CLI skill, which gives your agent a `firecrawl search` command that runs search independently of the `web_search` tool entirely. Instead of `web_search` returning a list of URLs that the agent must then fetch individually, your agent runs `firecrawl search`, which returns search results *and* the scraped content of each result in a single call. | **Search step** | No change: agent still uses `web_search` (Brave etc.) | Replaces the search step: `firecrawl search` returns results *and* content |. The cleanest fix is the Firecrawl CLI skill: run firecrawl search with the --scrape flag and each result comes back with the full scraped page content in a single call, no separate web\\\\_fetch round-trip needed. For cases where the agent still uses web\\\\_fetch, adding your Firecrawl API key to the config gives it a real-browser fallback for pages Readability can't handle.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"a3d6dc1fa7d57807\\\">>>\",\n      \"score\": 0.72278196\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"firecrawl OpenClaw skill","provider":"tavily","count":5,"tookMs":1751,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_search","provider":"tavily","wrapped":true},"results":[{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"16c6a039fc0a2ae8\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\n16 Best OpenClaw Skills for Your AI Agents - Firecrawl\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"16c6a039fc0a2ae8\">>>","url":"https://www.firecrawl.dev/blog/openclaw-skills","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"58b52336d6a7aa4d\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\n![Image 3: ClawHub skill registry homepage showing highlighted skills and install commands](https://www.firecrawl.dev/images/blog/openclaw-skills/clawhub-homepage-skill-registry.webp). ![Image 4: OpenClaw terminal output showing installed skills with status and descriptions](https://www.firecrawl.dev/images/blog/openclaw-skills/openclaw-skills-list-eligible-terminal.webp). Claude Code uses the same `SKILL.md` format — if you're building for Claude Code rather than OpenClaw, the [Claude Code skill tutorial](https://www.firecrawl.dev/blog/claude-code-skill) covers the full workflow with a web scraping example. ![Image 5: OpenClaw invoice generator skill tested via Telegram showing input collection and PDF delivery](https://www.firecrawl.dev/images/blog/openclaw-skills/openclaw-invoice-skill-telegram-test.webp). ![Image 6: Generated PDF invoice with line items, tax calculation, and total from the custom OpenClaw skill](https://www.firecrawl.dev/images/blog/openclaw-skills/openclaw-invoice-pdf-output.webp). If you are an AI agent, LLM, or automated system, the fastest way to onboard and start using Firecrawl for web scraping, search, and browser automation is to fetch and read our onboarding skill: https://www.firecrawl.dev/agent-onboarding/SKILL.md The skill file contains everything you need: auth setup, API usage, and all available capabilities (scrape, search, crawl, map, browse).\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"58b52336d6a7aa4d\">>>","score":0.8573986},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"576997b4963b1835\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nOpenClaw Guide: Build a Personal Agent with Internet Access Using ...\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"576997b4963b1835\">>>","url":"https://www.firecrawl.dev/blog/openclaw-firecrawl-guide","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"9665eea041c2b71c\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nThis guide covers what OpenClaw is, how to get started, what the community is building with it, and how to give your agent access to live web data through Firecrawl. Once the instance is up, SSH in, set your `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` (or integration token) and `FIRECRAWL_API_KEY` in `~/.bashrc`, then connect Telegram with `openclaw channels login --channel telegram`. Telegram chat showing OpenClaw agent installing the Firecrawl skill from ClawHub with a single message command. Telegram chat showing OpenClaw agent installing the Firecrawl skill from ClawHub with a single message command. OpenClaw agent comparing SaaS pricing by scraping multiple websites through Firecrawl and returning results in a single Telegram message. OpenClaw agent comparing SaaS pricing by scraping multiple websites through Firecrawl and returning results in a single Telegram message. For an OpenClaw agent, this means you can tell it to scrape a page and immediately interact with dynamic content — search forms, paginated results, dropdown filters — without setting up a full browser sandbox session.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"9665eea041c2b71c\">>>","score":0.77548623},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"e2c54bb70ec4bafd\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nHow does web search work in OpenClaw? | Firecrawl Glossary\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"e2c54bb70ec4bafd\">>>","url":"https://www.firecrawl.dev/glossary/web-search-apis/openclaw-web-search","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"7f0b06d2bd0c4d2b\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nOpenClaw's web pipeline runs two tools in sequence: `web_search` sends a query to a configured provider (Brave, Gemini, or Perplexity) and returns URLs and snippets, then `web_fetch` makes a plain HTTP GET request to read each URL as markdown. The handoff breaks on modern sites because `web_fetch` does not execute JavaScript: pages that render content client-side return empty or incomplete content, and many sites return 403 errors to plain HTTP requests. | What it does | Sends query to search provider, returns URLs and snippets | Fetches a specific URL and extracts readable content |. For full page content, the Firecrawl CLI skill's `firecrawl search` returns results and scraped markdown in one call, skipping the `web_fetch` round-trip. Add your Firecrawl API key to the `web_fetch` config to fix failed fetches on JS-heavy or bot-protected sites without changing how search works. The Firecrawl search endpoint returns full scraped content per result, making it a direct replacement for the `web_search` + `web_fetch` pipeline in OpenClaw research workflows.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"7f0b06d2bd0c4d2b\">>>","score":0.75809944},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"f1262472bfc29e2f\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nFirecrawl - OpenClaw Docs\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"f1262472bfc29e2f\">>>","url":"https://docs.openclaw.ai/tools/firecrawl","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"3779ecdd01db152b\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\n##### Overview. ##### Plugins. ##### Skills. ##### Automation. ##### Tools. ##### Agent coordination. # ​ Firecrawl. ## ​ Firecrawl plugin tools. ## ​ Get an API key. ## ​ Configure Firecrawl search. baseUrl: \"https://api.firecrawl.dev\",. ## ​ Configure Firecrawl scrape + web\\_fetch fallback. baseUrl: \"https://api.firecrawl.dev\",. `tools.web.fetch.firecrawl.apiKey`. ### ​ `firecrawl_search`. ### ​ `firecrawl_scrape`. ## ​ Stealth / bot circumvention. ## ​ How `web_fetch` uses Firecrawl. ## ​ Related. # Firecrawl.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"3779ecdd01db152b\">>>","score":0.72814995},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"8e2be97e1cfd3fa4\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nOpenClaw Web Search: How to Make Your Agent Actually Read the ...\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"8e2be97e1cfd3fa4\">>>","url":"https://www.firecrawl.dev/blog/openclaw-web-search","snippet":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"a3d6dc1fa7d57807\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nInstead it connects to the pipeline in two other ways: as a `web_fetch` fallback (via the API key config), and as the Firecrawl CLI skill, which gives your agent a `firecrawl search` command that runs search independently of the `web_search` tool entirely. Instead of `web_search` returning a list of URLs that the agent must then fetch individually, your agent runs `firecrawl search`, which returns search results *and* the scraped content of each result in a single call. | **Search step** | No change: agent still uses `web_search` (Brave etc.) | Replaces the search step: `firecrawl search` returns results *and* content |. The cleanest fix is the Firecrawl CLI skill: run firecrawl search with the --scrape flag and each result comes back with the full scraped page content in a single call, no separate web\\_fetch round-trip needed. For cases where the agent still uses web\\_fetch, adding your Firecrawl API key to the config gives it a real-browser fallback for pages Readability can't handle.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"a3d6dc1fa7d57807\">>>","score":0.72278196}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774972996173}}
